16. Session update — bug fixes and §12/§14 follow-through
This section covers a follow-up investigation session run against the actual
`player_anims.anm` binary plus the real `parser.py` (both unavailable in the
prior session, which had only the investigation script and this writeup).
All findings below are freshly re-derived from the file, not copied from
earlier text — see §17–18 for the specific bytes/addresses checked.
16.1 Bug fix: `count_u16_bone_list()` overcounts past the true boundary
Status: FIXED in `eagl_anm_investigate.py`.
The "stop when the next u16 equals `0xc6e4`" heuristic in
`count_u16_bone_list()` is not sufficient on its own. Concrete case (clip 99,
the bone-20/r08 list at `0x18b20c`):
The clean, genuinely-ascending keyframe-index run is 53 entries
(`1, 2, 3, 4, 6, 7, 8, 9, ... 63, 66`).
Immediately after entry 53, the bytes are a compact byte-form bone list
(`0a 0b 0c 0d 17 18 19` → bones `10, 11, 12, 13, 23, 24, 25`), then a
`00 00` pad, then the next track's `0xc6e4` header.
Because the byte-list's values, reinterpreted as big-endian u16, still
happen to be ascending for a few more "entries" (`2571, 3085, 5912, 6400`),
the old scan kept consuming past the real list end and stopped only at
entry 57 — a 4-entry overcount, with no error or warning.
Surveyed impact: checked 133 tracks file-wide that have both a `+0x08`
reloc and a usable `+0x0c` `hi` value. 24 of 133 (~18%) had a scan-only
length that disagreed with `hi − 1`. This is a materially bigger error
source than the `hi − 1` relationship's own ~5.4% imperfection noted in §10
— meaning most of the "94.6% match rate" gap was actually scan-overcounting,
not genuine exceptions to the `hi − 1` rule.
Fix: `count_u16_bone_list()` now accepts an optional `expected_len`
parameter. Pass `hi - 1` whenever it's available (i.e. whenever the list was
reached via a track's `+0x08` reloc, where `hi` is the track header's
`+0x0c` high halfword) and the function stops there exactly, ignoring the
magic-byte heuristic entirely past that point. Without `expected_len`, the
old scan-only behavior is preserved for backward compatibility / exploratory
use where no `hi` is available yet.
Updated guidance: treat `hi − 1` as the authoritative length signal,
not a thing to be validated against the scan. The scan is the unreliable
signal, not the other way around.
16.2 §14 priority 5 revisited: `+0x10`–`+0x13` is the per-track pointer array, confirmed directly
§5 suspected the clip header's per-track pointer array continues past
`+0x14` but only had 3 dumped pointers to go on. This session confirmed it
directly while chasing an unrelated lead (§17 below): `clip_off + 0x14`
is a real ELF relocation pointing at another track's header
(`0x18b0b8` → word `0x0015c6e4`, i.e. bone index 21, `0xc6e4` magic). This
is exactly the expected shape of the 4th slot in the per-track pointer
array (`+0x0c` = track 0, `+0x10` = track 1, `+0x14` = track 2 = bone 21
here), not a coincidence — it's ordinary continuation of the array §5
already described, just not previously confirmed by direct reloc lookup.
No new bytes were dumped beyond this single confirmation; the recommendation
from §5 (re-dump the full `n_bones × 4`-byte window from `+0x0c`) still
stands as future work.
