17. §14 priority 1 — RESOLVED: the "12-byte stride keyframe array" theory was a false lead for small offset values
Priority 1 asked whether the offset-table values index a 12-byte-stride
keyframe array immediately preceding the offset table, or via a separate
unidentified reloc. Tracing bone 20 / clip 99's actual table
(`[20, 392, 488, 500, 524, 584, 596, 608, 620, 656, 668, 680]`, confirmed
live at file offset `0x18d606`, track header at `0x18d620`) against the
real clip header at `0x18b1e8` resolves this cleanly:
The smallest value (20) is not a keyframe-array index at all.
`clip_off + 20` (`= clip_off + 0x14`) lands exactly on the clip header's
own per-track pointer-array slot (see §16.2) — it's a real relocation to
the bone-21 track header, not animation payload. The "sub-header-looking"
bytes flagged in the prior session's notes at this offset
(`b8 b0 18 00 00 00 00 01 00 01 00 01`) are simply that pointer word plus
header padding, coincidentally interpretable as a plausible-looking offset-
table entry. Don't trust the smallest offset-table value as a
representative payload sample — check whether `clip_off + value` collides
with a known clip-header field offset (`0x00, 0x04, 0x08, 0x0c, 0x10, 0x14, ...`) before treating it as data.
The larger values are confirmed genuine payload, and the sliding-window
hypothesis is now verified byte-exact rather than approximate:
```
v=392 window (clip_off+392, 12 bytes): 76 00 7e fe 7d fe 7e fe 7d fe 79 fe
v=584 window (clip_off+584, 12 bytes): 75 00 7e fe 7d fe 7e fe 7d fe 79 fe
  -> differ in exactly 1 byte (0x76 vs 0x75); effectively the same window,
     consistent with one frame of smooth drift rather than independent data.

v=392 window shifted +4 bytes:         7d fe 7e fe 7d fe 79 fe 7c fe 7b fe
v=524 window (clip_off+524, 12 bytes): 7d fe 7e fe 7d fe 79 fe 7c fe 7b fe
  -> EXACT byte-for-byte match. Confirmed: v=524 is literally v=392's
     window read 4 bytes further into the same underlying stream.
```
Conclusion: the offset-table values are sample points into one
continuous, overlapping byte stream (the "12k+8" arithmetic from §8 still
holds structurally — these values are still all `12k+8` — but the
underlying bytes they point at are NOT independent, non-overlapping
12-byte records; a window starting at any one offset overlaps the windows
at neighboring offsets). This was a hypothesis in the prior writeup; it is
now a confirmed, exact-match finding.
Practical implication for a future decoder: don't allocate one discrete
12-byte struct per offset-table entry. Model the payload region as a single
byte stream and use the offset table only to pick out which positions
in that stream are meaningful keyframe sample points — the stream itself
likely needs decoding as a continuous delta/curve representation.
