18. §14 priority 2 — partial progress: de-interleave reproduced exactly, quantization decode inconclusive (same as before, with one new data point)
Re-ran the even/odd de-interleave on a freshly-pulled 64-byte window at
`clip_off + 392` (clip 99, bone 20) rather than reusing the prior session's
numbers:
```
even (signed s8): 118, 126, 125, 126, 125, 121, 124, 123, [jump] ...
odd  (signed s8):   0,  -2,  -2,  -2,  -2,  -2,  -2,  -2, [jump] ...

even deltas (first 7): +8, -1, +1, -1, -4, +3, -1
odd  deltas (first 7):  -2,  0,  0,  0,  0,  0,  0
```
This independently reproduces the earlier-reported pattern almost exactly
(prior notes: even `+9,−1,+1,−1,−4,+3,−1`, odd flat at `−2`) — the 1-count
discrepancy on the very first delta is most likely just a different
starting alignment into the same cycle, not a contradictory signal. Both
channels jump sharply at the same byte index (index 8 in this window),
reconfirming a real structural boundary rather than noise.
New this session — quantization decode attempt against the float run:
applied `value = s8/127 * scale[c] + bias[c]` (c = component index mod 3)
to the smooth pre-jump even-channel segment, using this track's actual
float run (`scale ≈ (0.00314, 0.0688, 0.0254)`, `bias ≈ (0.00066, 0.0236, 0.00199)` — all six floats are small, well under 1.0, distinct from the
size-108-track float run dumped in the prior session, which had larger
values up to 0.28).
Decoded triplet magnitudes: `0.09577` then `0.09503` for two consecutive
windows — not unit-length (rules out, or at least doesn't support, a
