24. Quaternion / "smallest-three" rotation decode — tested rigorously; initial positive signal does NOT survive a proper statistical control
24.1 Initial test (clip 99, bone 20 = r_hand): looked very promising
Tried the standard "smallest-three" compressed-quaternion technique:
treat the 3 decoded float-run components as `(x, y, z)` of a delta
rotation (relative to bind pose, not the absolute bind quaternion), and
reconstruct the 4th component as `w = sqrt(1 - x² - y² - z²)`, valid only
when `x²+y²+z² ≤ 1`.
On clip 99 / bone 20's idle sample: all 30 sliding-window triplets
across the 32-byte even channel were valid (sumsq ≤ 1.0 in every case),
with reconstructed `w` tightly clustered in 0.9954–0.9994 — strongly
consistent with a near-identity delta rotation, exactly what you'd expect
for a subtle idle hand animation. This looked like a strong confirmation.
24.2 Broader survey (43 bone-20 tracks): looked even better at first — 90.2% valid
Ran the same test across every private (non-shared-default) bone-20 track
file-wide: 1054/1168 sliding-window triplets (90.2%) were valid, and
37 of 43 tracks (86%) were 100% valid.
24.3 Critical correction: most of that 90.2% was trivially guaranteed, not evidence
Before accepting 24.2 as confirmation, checked the maximum possible
sumsq for each track, computed from its own scale/bias as
`max_sumsq = Σ(|scale_c| + |bias_c|)²` (the value sumsq would take if
every decoded component hit its theoretical extreme). This revealed that
only 6 of the 43 tracks have a max_sumsq that could ever exceed 1.0 —
for the other 37, every possible byte value decodes to a sumsq below 1.0
regardless of which formula is used, because their scale/bias values are
simply too small. The "90.2% valid" and "86% of tracks 100% valid"
headline numbers from §24.2 are therefore mostly an artifact of testing
mostly-trivial cases, not real evidence for the smallest-three hypothesis.
Restricting to only the 6 tracks where the test could actually
discriminate (`0x108190, 0x1a0224, 0x312b14, 0x1d60e8, 0x0ecb5c, 0x19ddb4`):
```
0x108190: 13/44 valid (30%)
0x1a0224: 20/36 valid (56%)
0x312b14:  0/36 valid (0%)
0x1d60e8: 19/20 valid (95%)
0x0ecb5c:  0/28 valid (0%)
0x19ddb4:  6/8  valid (75%)
------------------------------
combined: 58/172 valid = 33.7%
```
The baseline for a uniformly random point inside the `[-1,1]³` cube
satisfying `sumsq ≤ 1` (i.e. landing inside the inscribed unit ball) is
52.4% (`(4/3)π / 8`). The non-trivial-only result, 33.7%, is below
random chance, and the per-track spread (0% to 95%) is wide and
inconsistent rather than clustering near either "always valid" or "always
invalid." This is a negative-to-inconclusive result, not a
confirmation — the smallest-three hypothesis does not hold up once
trivial cases are excluded.
24.4 What this does and doesn't rule out
This does not disprove rotation as the physical quantity — it
specifically tests one decode formula (per-component `s8/127 * scale + bias`, smallest-three reconstruction, `c = sliding_window_index % 3`
component assignment) and finds it doesn't hold rigorously. Plausible
remaining issues with the formula itself, not yet tested:
Component assignment may not be a simple `i % 3` sliding window — the
byte-16 sub-boundary (§21.2) suggests the 64-byte period may have
internal structure that a flat sliding window ignores.
The odd channel (still untested as a quaternion component — see open
item below) might supply one of the 4 components directly instead of
being reconstructed, with the even channel supplying the other 2 plus
something else.
§24.1's apparent success on clip 99 specifically may be because that
track happens to be one of the 37 "trivial" tracks (worth confirming
directly — if `0x18d620`'s own max_sumsq is comfortably under 1.0, its
30/30 result carries the same caveat as the broader survey's headline
number).
Recommended discipline going forward: for any future validity-style
test on this format (sumsq checks, range checks, etc.), always compute
the theoretical best/worst case from the track's own scale/bias first and
restrict claims of confirmation to tracks where the test is actually
capable of failing.
