non-trivial tracks.
However, applying the same trivial-case discipline from §24.3: the
180° bound turned out to be trivially satisfied for every track checked
(max possible angle per component ranged 1.8°–84.1°, computed from each
track's own scale/bias at byte extremes) — so "0 out of range" carries
little evidential weight on its own, the same trap as the earlier sumsq
test. The plausible magnitudes are still a mildly positive sign (the
scale/bias floats are at least consistent with rotation-angle-shaped
values rather than, say, being mis-typed as time or pixel data), but
range alone doesn't confirm the hypothesis.
26.3 Stronger test — per-component smoothness — fails
Applied a tougher check: isolate one component's values in temporal order
(both as a sliding window, `i%3`, and as non-overlapping groups) and look
for a smooth, gradually-changing curve, which is what real joint-angle
animation should produce frame to frame.
Result: not smooth, on either track tested. Component sequences
repeatedly toggle between two distinct value clusters rather than
drifting continuously — e.g. idle track (`0x18d620`) component 1:
`5.26°, 5.23°, 5.17°, −2.4°, −1.87°, 5.29°, −1.84°, −2.4°, 4.98°...` —
alternating between a "high" cluster (~5°) and a "low" cluster (~−2°)
rather than tracing one continuous path. Checked period-6 grouping as an
alternative to period-3 on the same data: same bimodal toggling pattern,
no improvement.
Looked at the raw sign pattern of the full 32-byte even channel
(`H`=positive, `L`=negative): `HHHHHHHH` for the first 8 bytes (matching
the byte-16 boundary structure already established in §21–22), then an
irregular `LLLHLLHLHLLHLHHHLLHLHL` mix with no fixed period — ruling out
a simple alternating-channel misread as the explanation for the
bimodality.
26.4 Honest status
No tested component-assignment scheme (sliding window mod 3, non-
overlapping groups of 3, or groups of 6) produces a smooth per-component
curve, on either the idle or high-motion track. This means the
plausible-looking Euler-angle magnitudes from §26.2 most likely reflect
the scale/bias floats being well-calibrated to a sane physical range,
but does not confirm that bytes are being assigned to components
correctly — the byte-to-component mapping itself is probably still
wrong, on top of whatever is true or false about the rotation-vs-position
question.
This reframes the remaining open question: it's less "is this
rotation or position" and more "what is the actual byte-to-component
