s16, LE s16, s8 sliding, s8 non-overlapping, period-6). On reflection
this is expected, not a new data point: an s16-BE value is numerically
dominated by its high byte, which is exactly the byte the s8 reading
already captures — so BE-s16 is mathematically near-equivalent to the
already-tested s8 reading, not an independent test. LE-s16 swaps which
byte dominates and did look briefly different on the first 3 samples
(component 0 clustered tightly near 0.0006 instead of jumping around),
but degenerated into the same toggling pattern past that point. No
variant of byte-width/endianness solves the smoothness problem — this
rules out byte-width/endianness as the missing piece, narrowing the
remaining open question further.
28.2 Unexpected, more useful finding: the full byte range is tightly centered around 128, not the signed extremes
While characterizing why the values looked bimodal, sorted the entire
32-byte even channel by unsigned value instead of signed (s8) value:
```
sorted (unsigned): 101, 117, 117, 117, 117, 117, 118, 118, 118, 120, 121,
123, 124, 125, 125, 126, 126, 127, 134, 134, 135, 135, 135, 137, 143,
152, 152, 153, 153, 153, 153, 159
```
Every value falls in the narrow band 101–159 — centered almost exactly
on unsigned 128, never near the true byte extremes 0 or 255. This had
been obscured by reading the bytes as signed (s8) first: values like
`159` and `101` read as `-97` and `101` respectively under two's-
complement, which made them look like they were clustering near the
signed extremes (±127) when actually, in unsigned terms, they're
tightly centered in the middle of the byte's range. 56 of 64 sampled
even+odd bytes (87.5%) fall within ±31 of 128; the remaining 8 are the
already-characterized flat `-2` cluster from the odd channel's first 8
positions (§18). There is zero data anywhere in the byte space outside
roughly [101, 159] ∪ {the near-zero cluster}.
This reframes the earlier "bimodal toggle between +120ish and -110ish"
language from §26.3 — that description was an artifact of reading
signed values that straddle the 128/-128 wraparound point. In unsigned
terms it's not really two far-apart clusters at all; it's one
continuous-looking band that happens to straddle the s8 sign boundary,
which is exactly the kind of thing that would make an `i%3` or any other
simple grouping look falsely bimodal even if the underlying data is
smooth — because a value can read as `+126` in one frame and `~140`
(`= -116` signed) in the very next frame despite being a small, real
change in the unsigned encoding.
