30. Predictor-with-sparse-correction model — strong, precise positive finding
Tested §29.4 priority 2 directly: instead of treating the 64-byte period
as N independent smooth channels, treat each period as a predictor of
the previous period, and look at only the bytes that actually change
between consecutive periods.
30.1 Idle clip (clip 99, bone 20): extremely clean result
Comparing period 0→1 and period 1→2 byte-for-byte (this re-derives and
sharpens the §22.2 finding, now framed correctly as same-position
inter-period prediction rather than intra-period variance):
```
period 0->1: 9/64 bytes changed
period 1->2: 6/64 bytes changed
```
Of the 15 total nonzero deltas across both transitions, 14 (93%) are
exactly +16 or -16, with the single exception being a -1 drift on the
one already-known calm-zone byte (position 0, the slowest-moving value
in the whole period). Every other changed byte moves by precisely one
quantization step of 16 — no other delta value appears even once.
30.2 High-motion track: same model, very different (and consistent) numbers
Ran the identical period-to-period predictor comparison on the
high-motion track (`0x312b14`, clip 226):
```
period 0->1: ~58/64 bytes changed
period 1->2: ~55/64 bytes changed (113/128 total across both transitions)
```
Deltas are scattered across the full byte range (`-225` to `+252`,
wrapping due to s8 overflow in several cases) with no repeated
quantization step — the delta histogram is close to flat, each value
appearing only once or twice out of 113 samples.
30.3 Interpretation
This is a clean, internally consistent picture rather than a
contradiction: in the idle clip, the underlying joint motion is so slow
that almost the entire 64-byte period is identical frame to frame,
and where it does move, it moves by the smallest possible quantization
step (16) — consistent with this being genuine LSB-level rounding noise
in an otherwise near-static signal, now confirmed precisely (93% exact
±16, not just "most deltas are similar") rather than just observed. In
the high-motion clip, large real joint rotation/translation changes
produce large, unconstrained deltas with no fixed step, because the
underlying value is actually moving fast enough that quantization noise
is no longer the dominant signal.
This reframes the smoothness failures from §26–29: those tests were
checking smoothness within a single period across components, which
this section's result suggests was the wrong axis to check. The actual
"smoothness" lives in the inter-period (frame-to-frame) direction,
matching a period to its physical role as one animation sample — not in
any intra-period byte ordering. The repeated failure to find a smooth
intra-period component sequence (§26–29) may simply mean intra-period
bytes were never meant to trace a smooth curve on their own; the
animation curve lives across periods, sampled once per 64-byte block,
exactly as the offset table and §21.2's block-comparison result already
implied.
