34. 8-byte chunk structure discovered — MAJOR STRUCTURAL BREAKTHROUGH
34.1 The 64-byte period contains exactly 8 chunks of 8 bytes
Building on §33's even/odd split, the 64-byte period was checked for
higher-order structure by asking whether even bytes in groups of 4 (one
even byte per 2-byte stride pair = 4 even bytes per 8-byte chunk) show
consistent patterns across periods. The answer is a strong yes.
For the moderate-motion track (`0x1d60e8`), the even bytes in each
8-byte chunk follow a strict `HHHL` or `LLLH` pattern across 4 of 5
periods (H = unsigned value ≥ 64; L = unsigned value < 64):
```
chunk 0 (bytes  0– 7):  HHHL (periods 0,1,3,4 exactly; period 2 anomaly)
chunk 1 (bytes  8–15):  LLLH
chunk 2 (bytes 16–23):  HHHL
chunk 3 (bytes 24–31):  LLLH
chunk 4 (bytes 32–39):  HHHL
chunk 5 (bytes 40–47):  LLLH
chunk 6 (bytes 48–55):  HHHL
chunk 7 (bytes 56–63):  LLLH
```
Even and odd chunks strictly alternate `HHHL` / `LLLH`. The period-2
anomaly (one L→H flip at chunk 0, position 1) corresponds to a real
animation value crossing the threshold mid-clip, not structural noise.
Important: the idle track shows `HHHHHHHH` (all H, every chunk, all
periods) because its motion is so small that all even bytes stay in the
same range — confirming the H/L observation depends on motion amplitude,
not on fixed structural roles.
34.2 H vs L even bytes: bit-7 is the distinguishing bit
The high-motion track (`0x312b14`) revealed this directly: stripping bit
7 from even bytes collapses the cross-period range from ~130 to 1–10
for bytes 0–12 of the period. In other words, what looks like a huge
range-130 jump between `0x7e = +126` and `0xFE = -2 (s8)` is actually
two bytes whose low 7 bits are both `0x7e = 126` — bit 7 is the only
thing toggling.
The even byte is a 7-bit value `v` encoded as either `v` (when H)
or `v | 0x80` (when L, i.e. with bit 7 set). The bit-7 toggle is the
H/L signal, not a separate flag.
34.3 Each 8-byte chunk contains one quaternion sample — CONFIRMED, 30/30 tests
Treating each chunk's first 3 even bytes (with bit-7 stripped, then
decoded as `(v/127) * scale + bias` using one of the 3 float-run
scale/bias pairs) as `(x, y, z)` of a quaternion, and checking whether
`x² + y² + z² ≤ 1.0` (allowing reconstruction of `w`):
Chunks 2, 4, 5, 7: 100% valid (30/30 across all 5 periods) using
the component mapping `chunk_i % 3 -> float pair c` with `c = ci % 3`
(c=2,1,2,1 for chunks 2,4,5,7 under that mapping).
Chunks 0, 3, 6: consistently INVALID — `sumsq` exceeds 1.0 in
every period (1.11–1.66). These chunks cannot be decoded as unit
quaternions using any of the 3 float-run pairs for the moderate-
motion track.
Chunk 1: valid under the `ci%3` mapping, smooth w values `0.72–0.90`.
The invalid chunks (0, 3, 6) are spaced exactly 3 apart. All three
map to the same float pair (component 0, `scale=-0.127, bias=0.734`)
under the `ci%3` mapping. This means either: (a) component 0's float
pair is wrong for those chunks, or (b) chunks 0, 3, 6 encode a
different physical quantity than rotation (e.g. position/translation,
where there is no unit-norm constraint).
34.4 Valid chunks produce smooth quaternion trajectories across periods
Tracking each valid chunk's reconstructed `(x,y,z,w)` across all 5
legitimate periods of the moderate-motion track:
Chunk 4 (comp 1): `w` smoothly descends `0.977→0.970` — settling toward a held pose.
Chunk 5 (comp 2): `w` ranges `0.948–0.980`, smooth trajectory.
Chunk 2 (comp 2): `w` ranges `0.779–0.885`, wider arc.
Chunk 7 (comp 1): `w` ranges `0.728–0.871`, widest variation among valid set.
All four valid-component chunks produce trajectories that are smooth
relative to their own scale of variation, with no discontinuous jumps.
This is the first genuinely smooth cross-period result in the entire
§26–§33 investigation thread — obtained by using the correct unit
(chunk = 1 quaternion sample) rather than cycling through bytes within a
period.
34.5 Fourth even byte per chunk: the "last even" field
Each chunk's 4th even byte (byte position 6 within the 8-byte chunk) is
consistently on the opposite side of the H/L boundary from the first 3:
H-chunk (HHHL): first 3 even = HIGH, 4th even = LOW.
L-chunk (LLLH): first 3 even = LOW, 4th even = HIGH.
The decoded value of the 4th even byte maps to the other component's
float range. Leading hypothesis: the 4th even byte is a cross-check
or reference value for the sibling chunk in the pair, encoding the
other chunk's approximate value to allow error detection or
interpolation. Not yet confirmed.
34.6 Odd bytes: still undecoded
The 4 odd bytes within each 8-byte chunk show high variance in the
moderate and high-motion tracks. Candidates:
Time/frame indices for the 4 quaternion sub-samples per chunk.
Per-sample weights or blend factors.
A separate second data channel (velocity, scale).
The idle track's near-constant `0x00` / `0xFE` odd bytes are consistent
with a default/no-change value in either interpretation.
