39. §38 priority 2 — MAJOR BREAKTHROUGH: component 0 is `w`, not an xyz axis; chunks group in THREES to form complete quaternions
39.1 The insight: component 0's scale/bias shape matches `w`, not `x`/`y`/`z`
Re-examined why component 0 (`scale=-0.127, bias=0.734` on the
moderate-motion track) consistently fails the "treat all 3 components as
xyz, derive w" test that works for components 1 and 2. The float values
themselves are the clue: component 0's scale is ~4x smaller than
components 1/2, and its bias (0.734) sits close to the maximum of the
decoded range — exactly the shape expected for a quaternion's `w`
component (which stays close to 1.0 and varies slowly for small/moderate
rotations, unlike x/y/z which scale with `sin(θ/2)` and can range more
widely). This was a formula-category error in every prior session's
attempt (§24 onward), not a structural problem with the chunks
themselves: component 0 was always being decoded as one more axis
component to feed into a unit-norm `sqrt`, when it should have been read
directly AS `w`.
